{{Infobox aircraft occurrence |name = 1934 Swissair Tuttlingen accident |occurrence_type = Accident |image = ETH-BIB-Curtiss AT-32C Condor, CH-170 am Boden in Dübendorf-Inlandflüge-LBS MH05-32-03.tif |image_size = |alt = |caption = CH-170, the aircraft involved in the accident, at Zurich's [[Dübendorf Air Base|Dübendorf airport]] earlier in 1934 |date = {{Start date|1934|07|27|df=y}} |summary = In-flight wing separation in severe weather conditions |site = Near [[Tuttlingen]], [[Germany]] |coordinates = |aircraft_type = [[Curtiss AT-32C Condor II]] |aircraft_name = |operator = [[Swissair]] |tail_number = CH-170 |origin = [[Zurich Airport]], [[Switzerland]] |stopover = [[Stuttgart Airport]], Germany |stopover0 = |stopover1 = |stopover2 = |stopover3 = |last_stopover = [[Leipzig/Halle Airport]], Germany |destination = [[Berlin Tegel Airport]], Germany |passengers = 9 |crew = 3 |injuries = |fatalities = 12 |survivors = 0 }}
The '''1934 Swissair Tuttlingen accident''' occurred on 27 July 1934 when a [[Swissair]] [[Curtiss AT-32C Condor II]] aircraft crashed near [[Tuttlingen]], [[Germany]] while flying through a [[thunderstorm]], killing all 12 people on board. It was the worst air crash in 1934<ref>{{cite web |url=http://aviation-safety.net/database/dblist.php?Year=1934 |title=1934 occurrences |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date= |website=aviation-safety.net |publisher=[[Flight Safety Foundation]] |accessdate=February 19, 2014}}</ref> and Swissair's first aviation accident since its foundation in 1931.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://aviation-safety.net/database/dblist.php?sorteer=datekey_desc&kind=%&cat=%&page=1&field=Operatorkey&var=5224 |title=Swissair occurrences |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date= |website=aviation-safety.net |publisher=[[Flight Safety Foundation]] |accessdate=February 19, 2014}}</ref> [[File:Nelly Diener grösser.jpg|right|thumb|The accident aircraft in the background, behind Nelly Diener, who died in the crash]]
==Aircraft and occupants== The aircraft involved in the accident, registered CH-170, was a [[Curtiss T-32 Condor II|Curtiss AT-32C Condor II]], a variant of the standard T-32 developed specifically for Swiss [[flag carrier]] [[Swissair]], which was its only operator. CH-170 had entered service on 28 March 1934 and, by the time of the accident, had only been in service for four months. The cabin was configured with seating for up to 15 people.<ref name="TDIA">{{cite web |url=http://www.thisdayinaviation.com/27-july-1934/ |title=This Day in Aviation - 27 July 1934 |author=Swopes, Brian |date= |website=thisdayinaviation.com |publisher= |accessdate=February 17, 2014}}</ref>
The aircraft's [[flight attendant]], [[Nelly Diener]], also known as the ''Engel der Lüfte'' ("Angel of the Skies"), is notable for being Europe's first air stewardess. She had been working for Swissair since 1 May 1934. The other two crew members were the pilot, Armin Mühlematter, and the radio navigator, Hans Daschinger. On the accident flight, there were nine passengers aboard.<ref name="TDIA"/><ref name="BAAA">{{cite web |url=http://www.baaa-acro.com/1934/archives/crash-of-a-curtiss-condor-32-in-tuttlingen-12-killed/ |title=Crash of a Curtiss Condor 32 in Tuttlingen: 12 killed |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date= |website=baaa-acro.com |publisher=Bureau of Aircraft Accidents Archives |accessdate=17 February 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140222235031/http://www.baaa-acro.com/1934/archives/crash-of-a-curtiss-condor-32-in-tuttlingen-12-killed/ |archive-date=2014-02-22 |dead-url=yes |df= }}</ref>
==Accident==
The aircraft departed [[Zurich]] for [[Berlin]], with stopovers in [[Stuttgart]] and [[Leipzig]]. Shortly after crossing the Swiss-German border, the aircraft, cruising at an altitude of about 3,000 meters, encountered a thunderstorm, and while flying through it, the right wing eventually broke off. This resulted in an immediate loss of control and the aircraft plummeted into a forest near [[Tuttlingen]], exploding into flames on impact.<ref name="TDIA"/><ref name="ASN0727">{{ASN accident|title=Swissair Curtiss AT-32C Condor II ''CH-170''|id=19340727-0 |accessdate=February 17, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.planecrashinfo.com/1934/1934-16.htm |title=Accident Details |last1=Kebabjian |first1=Richard |date= |website=planecrashinfo.com |publisher=Plane Crash Info |accessdate=17 February 2014}}</ref>
==Investigation==
Investigators found that oscillations in the wing had caused a stress fracture, the severity of which was exacerbated by the violent weather conditions in which the aircraft was flying. German investigators, however, determined that one fracture formed in the wing and engine mount structure due to defective construction and welding techniques in conjunction with the engine vibrations, while a second fracture resulted from the force of the turbulence in the storm.<ref name="TDIA"/><ref name="BAAA"/>
