{{Infobox company |name = Climate Change Capital |logo = [[Image:Ccc-social-logo.png|200px|Climate Change Capital]] |type = [[Private Limited Company]] |industry = Carbon Finance, M&A, Corporate and Project Finance Advice |foundation = {{start date and age|2003}} |location = London, [[United Kingdom]] |area_served = Worldwide, predominately Europe and Asia |products = Investments, Funds Management, Advice on Corporate Finance, Project Finance and M&A Transactions |homepage = {{URL|http://www.climatechangecapital.com}} }}
'''Climate Change Capital''' is a private [[asset management]] and advisory group founded in 2003 by Lionel Fretz and James Cameron to support efforts to develop solutions to climate change and resource depletion.
==History== The company established an advisory group in 2004 to provide financial, strategic and policy advice to energy-intensive industries, financial institutions, [[cleantech]] companies and governments.{{cn|date=May 2014}}
The asset management business, which was established in 2005, includes a carbon finance fund that invests in emission reduction projects, predominantly in developing countries, a private equity fund that invests in late stage technology and services companies headquartered in Europe<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-168650862.html|title=Investors prove their green credentials as Climate Change Capital raises AGBP135m.|publisher=Investment Adviser|date=September 10, 2007|subscription=yes|via=Highbeam|accessdate=May 6, 2014}}</ref> and a property fund that buys [[Green buildings|commercial green buildings]] or retrofits existing commercial properties in the United Kingdom.{{cn|date=May 2014}}
The company's think tank was established in 2009 to promote discussion of how capital can be deployed to mitigate and adapt to climate change.
In 2006, the group launched the world's largest private sector carbon fund.<ref>{{cite magazine|title=UK carbon fund launched.(Climate Change Capital)|publisher=Chemistry and Industry|date=September 18, 2006|subscription=yes|via=Highbeam}}</ref>
==Acquisition==
In April 2012, [[Bunge Limited|Bunge Ltd]], a global agribusiness and food company founded in 1818, acquired Climate Change Capital Group Limited.<ref name="Bunge Acquisition Of Climate Change Capital">{{cite web|title=Bunge Limited Completes Acquisition Of Climate Change Capital|url=http://uk.reuters.com/business/quotes/BG.N/key-developments/article/2520956|work=Reuters|accessdate=15 April 2013}}</ref>
==Senior management==
Climate Change Capital’s chairman is James Cameron, a member of [[General Electric|General Electric's]] ecomagination board, a trustee member of the [[UK Green Building Council]] and the [[Carbon Disclosure Project]]. Climate Change Capital's CEO is Eric Alsembach who also serves as the managing director of the Bunge Asset Management group.
